# TypeScript React Guidelines

## Prefer functional components

Use function components with typed props. Do not use class components.

```tsx
export function MyComponent({ title }: MyComponentProps) {
  // ...
}
```

## TypeScript React best practices

- Define explicit TypeScript interfaces or types for props (e.g. `GameButtonProps`); avoid `React.FC`
- Use `useState` and `useEffect` for state and side effects; prefer custom hooks when logic is reusable
- Use `React.memo` only when profiling shows a measurable benefit
- Keep strict TypeScript enabled; prefer type inference where it stays clear
- Colocate domain types in `src/react-app/lib/types/`

## Folder structure

```
src/react-app/
  components/     # UI components (screens, modals, spread, character, etc.)
  hooks/          # Custom hooks (use-game-screen, use-locale, etc.)
  providers/      # React context providers
  lib/            # Pure logic, storage, animation, tarot domain
  i18n/           # Locale strings and types
  App.tsx
  main.tsx
```

## Additional instructions

1. Use `.tsx` for files with JSX; `.ts` for logic-only modules
2. Respect strict TypeScript checks (`tsc --noEmit` must pass)
3. Use `React.lazy` and `Suspense` for code-splitting when adding heavy routes or screens
4. Prefer type inference for locals; be explicit for public APIs and props
5. Add error boundaries when introducing new top-level async or fragile UI trees
6. Follow existing naming: kebab-case files, PascalCase components, `use-*` hooks
7. Run ESLint with TypeScript and React plugins before finishing changes
